    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="div1" rend="DH-Heading1">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="normalweight" style="font-size:11pt">DARIAH (Digital Research Infrastructure for Arts and Humanities) coordinates the ATRIUM (Advancing fronTier Research In the arts and hUManities) project whose other main beneficiaries include research infrastructures in archaeology (ARIADNE), languages (CLARIN), and open scholarly communication in the social sciences and humanities (OPERAS). This project aims to consolidate and expand services as well as to facilitate access to a wide range of text, image and sound-based services across disciplines, languages and media in Arts and Humanities. One of the pillars of the ATRIUM project is to establish a common research assessment framework to incentivize a wide variety of research outputs. In this context, research infrastructures can contribute efficiently to reforming the research assessment framework (Tasovac et al 2023).</hi>
                </head>
            </div>
            <div type="div1" rend="DH-Heading1">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="normalweight" style="font-size:11pt">This poster</hi><ref n="1" target="ftn1"/>
                    <hi rend="normalweight" style="font-size:11pt" xml:space="preserve"> will focus on the current work within the ATRIUM project to develop a peer review framework in the field of Arts and Humanities and the challenges involved. Reviewing research articles is part of the everyday life of researchers and provides crucial insight into the questions and methods that are central to their community of research. Yet, reviewing can sometimes be challenging due to the range of disciplines, very technical dimensions or ethical issues encountered. On top of this, bias in academia privileges certain types of research outputs (like journal articles) over others (such as datasets, models, workflows or software). By building community consensus around a peer review framework, ATRIUM aims to incentivize a wide variety of research outputs that are necessary for building and maintaining innovative research infrastructures. In order to help valorize different types of research activities, we are working on developing an assessment framework and concrete evaluation grids for non-traditional research outputs. </hi>
                </head>
            </div>
            <div type="div1" rend="DH-Heading1">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="normalweight" style="font-size:11pt">In this poster, we will focus on presenting the grids for three types of research outputs: data papers (Jefferies et al. 2019), workflow papers (Atkinson et al. 2017) and submissions based on training materials (Sánchez et al. 2023). </hi>
                </head>
            </div>
            <div type="div1" rend="DH-Heading1">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="normalweight" style="font-size:11pt">This is part of DARIAH’s ongoing focus on research as a process rather than a product. In that context, we are advocating for process-based evaluation systems that recognize and reward all types of significant findings that may have been produced during the research process and not only in the final journal publication or a monograph: “it is not just the product, however incomplete, that [should be] seen as worthy of preservation for current and future generations, but also equally the process (or indeed processes) for producing it” (Lorella 2023).</hi>
                </head>
            </div>
            <div type="div1" rend="DH-Heading1">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="normalweight" style="font-size:11pt" xml:space="preserve">This research assessment framework will be concretely implemented in the newly founded </hi>
                    <hi rend="italic normalweight" style="font-size:11pt">Transformations</hi>
                    <hi rend="normalweight" style="font-size:11pt">(</hi>
                    <ref target="https://transformations.episciences.org/">
                        <hi rend="normalweight" style="font-size:11pt">https://transformations.episciences.org/</hi>
                    </ref>
                    <hi rend="normalweight" style="font-size:11pt">) journal launched by DARIAH in 2024 and hosted on the Episciences (</hi>
                    <ref target="https://www.episciences.org/publishing-model/">
                        <hi rend="normalweight" style="font-size:11pt">https://www.episciences.org/publishing-model/</hi>
                    </ref>
                    <hi rend="normalweight" style="font-size:11pt" xml:space="preserve">) Diamond Open Access platform. In this context, we consider </hi>
                    <hi rend="italic normalweight" style="font-size:11pt">Transformations</hi>
                    <hi rend="normalweight" style="font-size:11pt">’ open peer review model as central for improving the quality and transparency of the editorial workflow. </hi>
                </head>
            </div>
            <div type="div1" rend="DH-Heading1">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="normalweight" style="font-size:11pt" xml:space="preserve">The journal provides a trusted, non-commercial platform for documenting various methodological and research activities in arts and humanities, including data gathering and processing, annotation and modeling, analysis and interpretation. It embraces ephemeral or experimental scholarly outputs, including descriptions and analysis of data collections and workflows, annotation practices, software tools and training materials, as well as traditional scholarly papers. As an academic journal with an infrastructural bent, </hi>
                    <hi rend="italic normalweight" style="font-size:11pt" xml:space="preserve">Transformations </hi>
                    <hi rend="normalweight" style="font-size:11pt">prioritizes the integrity, reproducibility and sustainability of research practices in the arts and humanities.</hi>
                </head>
            </div>
            <div type="div1" rend="DH-Heading1">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="normalweight" style="font-size:11pt" xml:space="preserve">The evaluation assessment framework as part of ATRIUM will not only benefit the concrete use case of </hi>
                    <hi rend="italic normalweight" style="font-size:11pt" xml:space="preserve">Transformations, </hi>
                    <hi rend="normalweight" style="font-size:11pt" xml:space="preserve">but will serve as part of DARIAH’s contribution to the </hi>
                    <ref target="https://www.dariah.eu/2022/12/20/dariah-joins-the-coalition-for-advancing-research-assessment/">
                        <hi rend="normalweight" style="font-size:11pt">CoARA commitments</hi>
                    </ref>
                    <hi rend="normalweight" style="font-size:11pt" xml:space="preserve"> and promote wider recognition of innovative outputs within the research assessment landscape.</hi>
                </head>
            </div>
        </body>
